# Design Specification â€“ Series types in the Roi Chart Library

## Introduction

This document describes the various series types / visualizations supported by the roi chart library. As multiple charts support the same series types, this document is referred to from multiple chart design specifications (e.g. the bar chart and column chart design specification).

## Series types

The individual elements displayed in a chart are called series. How the series is displayed depends on the series type.

The following series types are supported:

- Line series
  - Standard
  - Dashed
  - Undecorated
  - Forecast

- Bar series / column series
  - Standard
  - Bullet
  - Forecast
  - Inset

- Dot series
- Target series
- Candlesticks
- Area series
- Value range series
- Prognosis series

Not all of them are supported in all chart types. The meaning of the individual series types is explained in the following sections.

### Line series

Line series are mostly used in column charts, but there are some cases where they also are used in bar charts, e.g. to show a target value which is the same for all bars. Most line styles from the column chart are also supported in the bar chart:

- Forecast (only column chart)

The forecast line series only differs from the standard line series in that from a certain category on it switches from a standard line to a dashed line. It&#39;s typically used when showing a timeline on the category axis, and actual data is only available until a certain point in time.

### Bar series / column series

##### Standard bars (only bar chart):

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

##### Standard columns (only column chart):

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Standard bars / columns have a width of 65% related to the available space for the category by default, which means 35% is whitespace, which is distributed evenly above and below or left and right of the bar / column. It is possible to specify the width if desired (e.g. 90% instead of 65% to make the gaps between the bars / columns smaller).

##### Bullet bars / columns

Bullet bars / bullet columns are essentially bars / columns with a decreased width:

Bar chart example:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Column chart example:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

The default width of bullet series is 18%.

The typical use case is to combine them with standard bars / columns for a bullet chart:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,) ![](data:image/*;base64,)

As the width can also be modified for standard bars, this series type is a convenience / helps with standardizing the appearance of bullet bars.

##### Forecast columns (only column chart)

Similar to standard columns, but will be shown with a reduced alpha value after a certain data point.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

##### Inset

This will be a column which is 2 pixels wider than the standard column on each side and is displayed as an inset, so that in combination with a standard column a fill column can be built:

An inset bar is 2 pixels less wide than the standard bar on each side and is displayed as an inset, so that in combination with a standard bar a fill column can be built:

![](data:image/*;base64,)

Like this but without the red line and without the stacking. The columns in the background would be one column, the inset, which is a little wider than the column in the foreground.



### Dot series

Dot series draw a circle at the point where the bar would end if it was a bar series. The diameter of the circle is fixed, but if the category height decreases so that it is smaller than the diameter, the diameter will be adjusted to the category height. This way the circle cannot exceed the available category space.

### Candlesticks

Candlesticks are usually used for showing percentage or absolute deviations. They typically use different colors for the candle stick tip, based on the value of the chart item.

Bar chart examples:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Column chart examples:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

The so called needle connects the tip with the origin. The tip can be either a circle, a triangle or a rectangle, where the center is located at the value position. The color of the tip is typically determined by the value, e.g. negative values in gray and positive values in red.





### Area series

Area series fill the area below the value with the fill color.

**One value:**

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

If the area series only has one value, then the area will be drawn between the origin and the value.

**        Two values:**

![](data:image/*;base64,)

In this case the area is filled between the two values.



### Value range

The value range series shows a bar/column between two values min and max, plus a circle at the actual value. It is typically used in combination with a line series to show a value in combination with a range. The width of the column / height of the bar is limited to 8 pixels, thus in the example below when increasing the width of the chart the column won&#39;t become wider than 8 pixels.

This screenshot shows only the value range series:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Some columns look as if they had a rounded top, because the actual value is the same as the max value. The color of the circle (8 pixel diameter, same logic as the column) matches the color of the column, thus the circle is not visible.

Here is an example where a value range series is displayed in combination with a line series:

### Prognosis

The prognosis series are used to show three values at the same time â€“ the actual value, the low value and the high value. The actual value is drawn with a small circle, the high and low values are drawn as a range limited through bars. Here is an example:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

When decreasing the width of the chart, the horizontal lines at the top and bottom of the range decrease in width. The circle stays the same until there is not enough space available any more.
